(2019, 1, '2023-04-03 04:49:58', '2023-04-03 04:49:58', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are a few govt. own places of attraction in Bangladesh and Tajhat Palace is one of them which is stunning in beauty and gigantic in size. It is a specimen of the historical palace which was built at the beginning of the 20th Century. This old building is converted into a museum in the present time, is three kilometers southeast of Rangpur city center.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Construction of Tajhat Palace</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://www.travelandexplorebd.com/storage/app/public/posts/April2020/Tajhat%20palace%20first%20pick.jpg\" alt=\"Tajhat palace\" title=\"Front View of ajhat palace\"/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">Front View of Tajhat Palace - Photo Credit:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.google.com.bd/maps/place/Tajhat+Palace/@25.7428852,89.2748914,3a,75y,90t/data=!3m8!1e2!3m6!1sAF1QipO6bGsa_Jlqn45whiZwHaG6JcLo7eiNc8lGlp_X!2e10!3e12!6shttps:%2F%2Flh5.googleusercontent.com%2Fp%2FAF1QipO6bGsa_Jlqn45whiZwHaG6JcLo7eiNc8lGlp_X%3Dw114-h86-k-no!7i4000!8i3000!4m5!3m4!1s0x39e32db15873de0b:0x95440457e2745c92!8m2!3d25.7252732!4d89.2799033?hl=en&amp;authuser=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Arman Habib Raihan</a></figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>About 76 meters long, 2 stories of the edifice, The Tajhat Palace has a spectacular front look. A ribbed conical dome supported by using a tall octagonal neck is positioned in the middle of the roof and crowns the palace. The railing initially featured marble sculptures of conventional Roman figures, those have disappeared since long back.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>These are just some of the superb aspects that continue to attract visitors from around the world to this small corner of the earth.&nbsp; This 100-year-old palace is truly a superstructure and visitors often discover themselves astonished by the details of craftsmanship that is found in every corner of this edifice.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The material, white stones, marbles stone, limestone and redbrick were used to build this magnificent palace were imported from different parts of the subcontinent. There were 2000 people worked together to build this royal palace and spent almost 1.5 million USD the then time.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Tajhat represents what?</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://www.travelandexplorebd.com/storage/app/public/posts/April2020/The%20dom%20of%20Tajhat%20Palace.jpg\" alt=\"Tajhat palace\" title=\"Tajhat palace\"/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">Tajhat Palace - Photo Credit:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/2a/Tajhat_Palace_-_Front_Gombuj.jpg\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">wikimedia.org</a></figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The name Tajhat came from where? No one knows exactly but, the historian says that Gopal Lal Roy was a jeweler by profession who migrated from Panjab up to Rangpur and made his fortune here. As was a jeweler and he worked with the golden “Taj” means crown and “hat” means Local Bazar. Later he became the Zamindar of Tajhat estate as a minor after his father passed away.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This palace also was a place to celebrate the Pahela Baishak (Bengali New Year) along with the “Bau Mela” (fair of wives) for women. There was another type of festival was celebrated in this palace called “Kite Festival” for the children during the Pahela Baishak (the first two days of Bengali new year).&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Conversion from a palace into a museum</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://www.travelandexplorebd.com/storage/app/public/posts/April2020/17180909765_fc92cf1154_c.jpg\" alt=\"Corridor of Tajhat Palace \" title=\"Corridor of Tajhat Palace \"/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">Corridor of Tajhat Palace - Photo Credit:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.flickr.com/photos/arghyabanik/17180909765/in/photolist-PveeGP-YN4r9T-YwNZTs-T9YUXo-2aSAEky-8Kc8ZK-9wkQyr-25n6Kba-kR81jb-sbdDUa-fw9xpe-qs7LYw-27HohKw-Q7z6Jh-9WzV8H-dBhERH-9WzUVp-9WCMq3-Kwoakv-7iYwbf-Cvg5zX-THtpQq-6XERNj-p6SGZW-NkKKa7-Y7oErm-2cNPH1M-MPq5DN-YHyseF-JtHPPE-HGxPNj-JtHPtu-6XERPu-boRgpX-22UutFm-EY4mGB-NkKKCm-D9j4tW-XKsSPE-hfCjaZ-fM5BMf-apHpG2-q3uysr-21tYX91-JtHQfj-9Jsc2-25sfUuj-21Xjsku-GaLan5-2hC74X5\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Arghya Banik (flicker)</a></figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>During the period of General Ershad, this palace was used as a Rangpur High Court Brach of the Supreme Court of Bangladesh from 1984 to 1991. Later, in 1995, the Department of Archaeology has declared this place as a protected monument.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To recognize the architectural value, the Government of Bangladesh has converted the 2nd floor of this palace into Rangpur museum in 2005. Then there are also some terracotta relics of the 10th and 11th century on the 2nd and 3rd floor and there also you will find some materials used by Maharaj Gopal Lal Roy the then time in the palace.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are also some manuscripts, including some copies of Mahavarat, Ramayan and a Quran. In rooms in the backside, you will also find some black stone Hindu carvings that are mainly of the deity Vishnu. Photography inside the museum premises is prohibited.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Opening and closing time of Tajhat Palace</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://www.travelandexplorebd.com/storage/app/public/posts/April2020/tajhat%20palace%20back%20side%201.jpg\" alt=\"Tajhat Palace\" title=\"Tajhat Palace\"/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">Tajhat Palace Back Side - Photo Credit:&nbsp;Ibrahim Husain Meraj&nbsp;</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>From 10.00 am to 06.00 pm, Tajhat Palace is open for the visitors 7 days a week.&nbsp; However, the museum located on the 1st floor of the palace has a timetable as below. Only on Sunday, the museum will remain closed but the palace will remain open all the time.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>During Eid Holidays:</strong>&nbsp;Tajhat Palace will remain closed for visitors during Eid day and the previous day of Eid but It will remain open as usual from the next day of Eid day.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Timing during Ramadan:</strong>&nbsp;Tajhat Palace will be closed just at 04. 00 PM during the holy month of Ramadan.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>All Govt. Holidays:&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;Tajhat Palace will remain closed during any govt. holiday.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Check out our&nbsp;<a href=\"https://travelandexplorebd.com/tour-category/Archaeological%20Tours\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Archaeological Tour&nbsp;</a>to visit such nice edifice of the north Bengal region of Bangladesh</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Tajhat Palace', 'There are a few govt. own places of attraction in Bangladesh and Tajhat Palace is one of them which is stunning in beauty and gigantic in size', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '2017-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-04-03 04:49:58', '2023-04-03 04:49:58', '', 2017, 'http://localhost/wordpress/news-site/?p=2019', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(2020, 1, '2023-04-03 04:52:36', '2023-04-03 04:52:36', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Sat Gambuj mosque is one of the well-preserved mosques in the ancient Mughal capital Dhaka, located now in the Mohammadpur area of the city</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The mosque building is positioned on the western end of a raised&nbsp;<em>shan</em>&nbsp;or courtyard&nbsp;measuring&nbsp;26.82m long and 25.60m wide, which is encompassed by a low boundary wall with a gateway in the middle of the eastern side. This arched gateway is located at the central axis of the courtyard and the mosque building. A flight of steps leads to the rooftop of the gateway from the north and south side.&nbsp;The mosque building is oblong in plan, measuring 8.22m wide by 17.67m long externally. The mosque is entered from the east by three&nbsp;cusped arched&nbsp;openings,&nbsp;which leads directly to a niche in&nbsp;the&nbsp;<em>kibla&nbsp;</em>or western wall. As a result, the&nbsp;<em>kibla&nbsp;</em>wall&nbsp;has three&nbsp;arched&nbsp;<em>mihrab&nbsp;</em>niches, the central one&nbsp;being larger than the flanking ones. All the entrance archways are framed by recessed panels in the wall.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://whythisplace.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/sixty-dome-mosque-1024x576.jpg\" alt=\"The Sixty Dome Mosque Bangladesh\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Sixty dome mosque is one of the oldest mosques, built in 1459 with amazing architectural&nbsp;structure. You will find it in Bagerhat, Bangladesh.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For it’s glorious history and beauty&nbsp;UN&nbsp;has declared it as&nbsp;world heritage&nbsp;site.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It is a Tughlaq styled mosque.&nbsp;Khan Jahan Ali&nbsp;was the architect and&nbsp;general contractor of this historical mosque. It is the largest&nbsp;historical mosque&nbsp;in Bangladesh. It is also one of the most impressive&nbsp;place on the Indian Subcontinent.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://whythisplace.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/the-sixty-dome-mosque-bangladesh.jpg\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\"><img src=\"https://whythisplace.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/the-sixty-dome-mosque-bangladesh-1024x683.jpg\" alt=\"Shat Gambuj Masjid (Sixty Dome Mosque) at Bagerhat, Bangladesh\"/></a><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\"><em>Shat Gambuj Masjid (Sixty Dome Mosque) at Bagerhat</em></figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Khan Jahan Ali was a great and famous muslim saint. He was the local&nbsp;ruler of Khalifabad (present Bagerhat). He was an officer of Bengal&nbsp;Sultan Nasiruddin Mahmud Shah. Khan Jahan Ali built a Muslim colony in this locality and built many structures for the well service for the people. He made water tanks, mosques etc. Shat Gambuj Mosque is his greatest creation which is now a world Heritage site.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Sultanate mosque, Shat Gambuj Mosque was also used for ruling the area and used as a court too.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The mosque is situated on the eastern bank of the Ghora Dighi. It is&nbsp;about 3 miles far from the main town of Bagerhat.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":2721,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://whythisplace.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/inside-sixty-dome-mosque-1.jpg\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\"><img src=\"https://whythisplace.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/inside-sixty-dome-mosque-1-1024x705.jpg\" alt=\"Inside of Shat Gombuj Mosque, Bangladesh\" class=\"wp-image-2721\"/></a><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\"><em>Inside of Shat Gombuj Mosque</em></figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The name Shat Gambuj Masjid means a mosque with sixty domes. But&nbsp;actually the mosque has 77 squat domes with 7 four sided pitched&nbsp;Bengali domes in the middle row. There are 11 arched doors on east and 7 each on north and south. The mosque is divided into 7 longitudinal aisles. There are 11 deep bays of stone columns. The wall of the mosque is 6 feet thick and the internal space is 160 feet into 108 feet. The full mosque is built by red burn mud or bricks.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The mosque is constructed in 1449 with terracotta decoration. Around the doors you can see beautifull design. Inside of the mosque the walls are designed by former muslim cultural tradition. The full&nbsp;mosque is a wonderfull archeological beauty which is the signature of&nbsp;15th century.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now there is a picnic spot beside the mosque area around the&nbsp;historical Ghora Dighi.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There is an old decorated boundary wall around the mosque yard. Muslim people pray Namaz in the mosque. Every Friday at noon about 5 thousand or more people go to pray Namaz in the historical Shat Gambuj Mosque.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There is a museum in the mosque area which is situated to keep the&nbsp;historical items safe. You can know a lot about the mosque and about&nbsp;the history of 15th century.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Foreigners are charged a little to see the mosque. Though you don’t&nbsp;want to see the museum you’ll have to pay to visit only the mosque.&nbsp;The entry fee is only 50 taka for foreigners including the fee of the&nbsp;museum. Museum is open from 9am to 12 pm and 2 pm to 5 pm.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":2722} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://whythisplace.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/bandarban-bangladesh-1024x742.jpg\" alt=\"bandarban bangladesh\" class=\"wp-image-2722\"/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">Photo by Amjad rana on Unsplash</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you go to visit the historical Shat Gambuj Mosque you can also&nbsp;visit some more historical places of Bagerhat. Bagerhat is a city of&nbsp;historical mosques,&nbsp;tombs and temples with some larger ponds which are historical and beautifull too. Rickshaw is available for local&nbsp;movement and it’s enough because all places are near the mosque.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Near the mosque there is only one very good res0taurant but no&nbsp;residence is situated here. You can see the whole Bagerhat town in a&nbsp;single day but you’ll have to stay at least a night to visit the whole&nbsp;district. Don’t worry, three very good hotels are in&nbsp;Bagerhat&nbsp;and one&nbsp;is at the Mongla Port.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So don’t miss to visit this wonderful world Heritage mosque quickly.&nbsp;You are bound to be lost in it’s beauty.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Sixty dome mosque is one of the oldest mosques in Bangladesh', 'The Sat Gambuj mosque is one of the well-preserved mosques in the ancient Mughal capital Dhaka, located now in the Mohammadpur area of the city\n\nThe mosque building is positioned on the western end of a raised shan or courtyard measuring 26.82m long and 25.60m wide, which is encompassed by a low boundary wall with a gateway in the middle of the eastern side. This arched gateway is located at the central axis of the courtyard and the mosque building.', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '1963-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-04-03 04:52:36', '2023-04-03 04:52:36', '', 1963, 'http://localhost/wordpress/news-site/?p=2020', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
